##During the outbreak of road closures, domestic violence no car to escape, she and two children walk four or five hours, but also worry about not passing the checkpoint

Micro signal

Features an introduction to the refreshing flavor of the feminist hardcore

Recently, I've seen a lot of people talk about domestic violence during the epidemic, there are adults beating children, boys beating their girlfriends, domestic violence hasn't stopped because of the epidemic, in fact, it never went away. In these difficult times, the plight of the victims may be even more acute.

A while back, someone in my life was getting beat up.

Image courtesy of the web

This year, I went back to the northern hometown for the New Year, our county on the second day (January 26) began to seal off the city road, since then, nothing special, we have not even out the door.

On the morning of February 11th I heard my brother and sister crying and answering the phone. It was her sister J's son, S, who called her, saying that his mother had been beaten again by his father. Now her mother was dragging the suitcase and carrying him and his sister to our county seat.

J has been divorced for two years. Before the New Year, J's ex-husband with two children knelt down before J and begged him to come back with him to his hometown for the new year. His hometown is in another county, and the children were crying too. Each of the two children was sentenced to one. They seldom see each other, wants to spend New Year's together, so J has to agree to go to her ex-husband's house for New Year's. J is a particularly capable woman, have their own company, in the city has a house car, are self-made.

On hearing the news that J had been beaten, we were both angry and anxious, and discussed what to do at once. At that time, the car is not proven can not go on the road, however, what exactly to prove, we do not know, because we have not moved since the city closed.

I ran to the village committee with my brother to ask how to open the city certificate, and also let j's brother in the county town to ask how to open the county certificate, ready to quickly pick up her and the children.

Image courtesy of the web

It was only after arriving at the village committee that we realized how difficult it was to operate. If it was to go out of our county to pick up people from another county, this was strictly prohibited during the epidemic period, and our county's road trip proved that, checkpoints in other counties are likely to be disapproved.

At the same time, we were also faced with the possibility of not being allowed to return to the city after leaving the county seat. At that time, the Control Policy Changed Day by day. The Village Committee did not know how the county border checkpoint was managed. If we were trapped in the middle of the two county border checkpoints, we would be in trouble.

In addition, they are more than 20 kilometers away from the county boundary, it is very difficult to walk to. The propaganda at that time was that villages and villages did not pass, counties and counties did not pass, even if the county border, our county level checkpoint is very likely not to let in.

On one side are the difficulties of driving, on the other side are the mother and son who have been walking for several hours. The youngest sister is only 7 years old, and J is still dragging her suitcase. And they can't keep calling because they're on the road and have nowhere to charge their phones in case they run out of juice.

While we try to open a certificate, while suggesting J must call the police, contact the police station, if our car can not enter the other county, see if the police station can help to send to the county border side, then we can receive; If Our county does not allow outsiders to come in, we can ask the police station to help them find a place to live.

At the time we assumed that the police might not be involved in domestic violence, but it was possible to contact a place of residence, like the truck driver on the news who had been stuck on the highway for several days and was later helped by the police.

Around 1:00 in the afternoon, we sealed the village seal with the help of our relations, but we still need to seal the village seal. The Village Committee cadres repeatedly told us: You can't get out, it's so strict now, no vehicle is allowed to go on the road for anything that is not particularly urgent, township will not give you seal, and see your travel reason is to go out of town to pick up people, this is even more impossible, perhaps also to pursue the responsibility of the village committee cadres to stamp this illegal certificate.

Image courtesy of the web

J later called 110, but the police did not respond, just told her that in this case, we can drive over to pick people up. We also doubted whether the police could be trusted. At that time, each county town and each village was in their own way. There were many places to persuade people to return to their homes. There were also checkpoints blocking the road. What we feared most was being stuck between two county checkpoints.

They walked mostly on country roads, had no restaurants, and had little to eat at noon. They said there were no cars on the road, the only one passing, they waved for a ride, the car did not stop. At that time, I was especially afraid of proving that I couldn't stamp the township's seal at last. If I couldn't reach them and the police didn't care, the three of them didn't eat. What should I do at night? It's very cold in winter in the north.

My brother said that if there was no other way, he would talk to her ex husband and ask him to take them back, to put up with them for a while, and wait for the epidemic to pass, and my sister said, well, if I beat you up, would you still live with me? My brother's not talking. I thought my younger brother's consciousness would be better after all these years of training and education with my younger sister and me, but now it seems that there is still room for improvement.

At first, my sister-in-law asked S. to call his father, hoping that he could talk through the children and get them to the county line, where we could try to pick them up. But his father didn't answer the phone, and then he called s's grandmother, and she said, "If you come back now, I'll pick you up. If you don't come back, do you think your father will? " And Hung Up.

In desperation, we had my brother-in-law contact j's ex-husband, because they had a brother-in-law, no hard feelings, and they still spoke. To do his ideological work, but can not provoke him, with emotion, emotional reasoning, reprimand plus emotional kidnapping, and finally he agreed to send them. There County car is not on the road, he rode a tricycle, and finally caught up with them. The three of them had been walking for four or five hours.

While we were worrying about whether we should go to the village and try to get a stamp, J's younger brother said he contacted a classmate who worked at the police station and managed to get a pass in the county seat, as long as they get to the county line, there's a good chance they will.

Later I asked them, the original county boundary was not so strict. They got off a tricycle on the other side of the county boundary and walked into our county town. Their ID card was from our county. J's younger brother received them on the county side and tore their hearts out for a day, it's finally over.

I was upset that J's ex husband, in such an extreme situation as the closure of the city during the outbreak, had physically assaulted J and Poker Face them for running away from home. He was so mean that he calculated that they would not go far in such a situation, and that they would have to go back to him in the end, out of all help.

Doesn't he dare to use violence again and again, just because it doesn't cost anything? His parents spoke on his behalf, the police did not respond, and the neighbours considered domestic violence a domestic matter, all of which contributed to the survival of domestic violence and made it difficult for victims to obtain support and justice.

Years ago, I put an anti-domestic violence pamphlet on my water cooler, and I told my family that violence is not only physical, but also verbal. So when I heard about J, my family and I decided to do everything we could to support her, that it wasn't her fault that she had been subjected to violence, and that it was wrong to blame the victim. Recognize that violence does not solve problems, that violence is a problem that needs to be solved.

A friend told me: no record is no record. I thought I should write this down. I can't leave the victims of domestic violence alone to deal with the injuries. It makes sense to give victims the support they can afford, not to treat domestic violence as a domestic issue, not to stand by and do nothing, to remove the soil from which it exists.
